<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="951" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d951">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/16670: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-06T12:00:00+07:00">June 6,
                                    1941—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 7—12:01 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>224. During air raid on Chungking between hours of 7 and 11 on evening of
                            June 5 Japanese planes also dropped bombs on south bank, one or more of
                            which landed about 400 yards behind Chancery while others hit sand bar
                            on foreshore about 400 yards from residence occupied by members of
                            Embassy staff causing slight damage from fallen plaster.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Department. Repeated to Shanghai, Peiping, Hankow. Shanghai
                            please repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>